An '''akamptisomer''' is a type of [[conformational isomer]] characterized by a [[hindrance|hindered]] inversion of a [[bond angle]]. It was first discovered in 2018 in a series of bridged [[porphyrin]] molecules.<ref>{{cite journal |journal= [[Chemical & Engineering News]] |title= Chemists claim they’ve defined the first new class of stereoisomers in 50 years |first= Sam |last= Lemonick |date= May 24, 2018 |volume= 96 |issue= 22 |url= https://cen.acs.org/physicalChemistry/chemicalBonding/Chemists-claim-ve-defined-first/96/i22 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1= Canfield |first1= Peter J. |last2= Blake |first2= Iain M. |last3= Cai |first3= Zheng-Li |last4= Luck |first4= Ian J. |last5= Krausz |first5= Elmars |last6= Kobayashi |first6=, Rika |last7= Reimers |first7= Jeffrey R. |last8= Crossley |first8= Maxwell J. |year= 2018 |title= A new fundamental type of conformational isomerism |journal=  Nature Chemistry |volume= 10 |pages= 615–624 |doi= 10.1038/s41557-018-0043-6|bibcode= 2018NatCh..10..615C }}</ref>

